T1  - Managerial Moral Strategies—In Search of a Few Good Principles
AU  - Soule, Edward
Y1  - 2002/01/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2002.5922420
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2002.5922420
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 114
EP  - 124
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The goal of this article is to help managers, students, and scholars contend with moral business problems by urging efforts to develop an adequate ?managerial moral strategy.? Integrative social contract theory (ISCT) is arguably the most promising candidate available, but a critical analysis reveals a shortcoming: it lacks sufficient moral content. Alleviating this weakness requires the formulation of the moral principles applicable to management. Doing so will elevate the usefulness and the influence of ISCT and the business ethics enterprise generally.
AB  - The goal of this article is to help managers, students, and scholars contend with moral business problems by urging efforts to develop an adequate ?managerial moral strategy.? Integrative social contract theory (ISCT) is arguably the most promising candidate available, but a critical analysis reveals a shortcoming: it lacks sufficient moral content. Alleviating this weakness requires the formulation of the moral principles applicable to management. Doing so will elevate the usefulness and the influence of ISCT and the business ethics enterprise generally.
