TY  - JOUR
T1  - Social Capital: Prospects for a New Concept
AU  - Adler, Paul S.
AU  - Kwon, Seok-Woo
Y1  - 2002/01/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2002.5922314
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2002.5922314
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 17
EP  - 40
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A growing number of sociologists, political scientists, economists, and organizational theorists have invoked the concept of social capital in the search for answers to a broadening range of questions being confronted in their own fields. Seeking to clarify the concept and help assess its utility for organizational theory, we synthesize the theoretical research undertaken in these various disciplines and develop a common conceptual framework that identifies the sources, benefits, risks, and contingencies of social capital.
AB  - A growing number of sociologists, political scientists, economists, and organizational theorists have invoked the concept of social capital in the search for answers to a broadening range of questions being confronted in their own fields. Seeking to clarify the concept and help assess its utility for organizational theory, we synthesize the theoretical research undertaken in these various disciplines and develop a common conceptual framework that identifies the sources, benefits, risks, and contingencies of social capital.
