TY  - JOUR
T1  - Religiosity and Ethical Behavior in Organizations: A Symbolic Interactionist Perspective
AU  - Weaver, Gary R.
AU  - Agle, Bradley R.
Y1  - 2002/01/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2002.5922390
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2002.5922390
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 77
EP  - 97
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Claims that religion can influence ethical behavior in business are plausible to many people but problematic in light of existing research. Our analysis indicates that religious role expectations, internalized as a religious self-identity, can influence ethical behavior. However, relationships of religious role expectations to behavior are moderated by religious identity salience and religious motivational orientation. We conclude by discussing the influence of organizational context on religious identity salience and the need for innovative and interdisciplinary empirical research on religion and ethical behavior in organizations.
AB  - Claims that religion can influence ethical behavior in business are plausible to many people but problematic in light of existing research. Our analysis indicates that religious role expectations, internalized as a religious self-identity, can influence ethical behavior. However, relationships of religious role expectations to behavior are moderated by religious identity salience and religious motivational orientation. We conclude by discussing the influence of organizational context on religious identity salience and the need for innovative and interdisciplinary empirical research on religion and ethical behavior in organizations.
